{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close",
    "objective": "Synthesize the identification of a TN-C-S system with the correct application of specific ADS conductors for circuits and services.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To master earthing and ADS, you must be able to look at a supply arrangement and immediately know which components are required to make it safe. In a TN-C-S (PME) system, the supply arrives with a combined neutral and earth, but the internal installation must treat them as separate. Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS) is only achieved when the correct conductors—the Earthing Conductor, the CPC, and the Main Protective Bonding—are all installed to provide a low-resistance path for fault current and to equalize potential across metal services."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are installing a new consumer unit in a property with a TN-C-S (PME) supply. To ensure the ADS system is compliant, you must connect the installation to the supplier's terminal, wire a new lighting circuit, and secure the incoming metallic water main. Identify the earthing system type and name the three specific green-and-yellow conductors required for these three distinct tasks.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "TN-C-S Earthing System",
      "Earthing Conductor (to connect the MET to the supplier's terminal)",
      "Circuit Protective Conductor / CPC (for the lighting circuit)",
      "Main Protective Bonding Conductor (for the metallic water main)"
    ],
    "hint": "Think about the specific names we use for conductors based on their job: one connects the whole house to the source, one protects an individual circuit, and one 'bonds' the metal pipes."
  }
}

